name: Spacious, Quiet Room
description: Kick back and relax in this calm, stylish space. Easy street parking. Centrally located.
host_about:
Hi there,
I am a healer, working with Hospice. I am inspired to drink life up, understanding that there is a finite amount of life to be had. I love to travel. My last amazing journey was to the Amazon. Even more memorable than the visual aspects of that trip were the auditory surprises. In addition to the contant vibrational buzzing and hissing in the air, I have 2 words for you, especially if you get to the Amazon: "Howler Monkeys". They truly sound like I imagine dinosaurs would sound. Apparently they get such volume and monster howl from a hole in a bone in their throats. Must be heard to be believed. But I digress! I'm a weekly dancer, pulling out the boots for two step, the retro wear for East Coast swing, and I waltz every chance I get no matter what I'm wearing. I love beautiful found objects. I write poetry and short stories. I have a private psychotherapy practice and teach mindfulness to people who are interested in more resiliency, more ZEST!  But I bet if you talked to my friends, they'd note the overall goofy, delighted way I like to carry on with life in general. As Helen Keller said, "Life is a banquet, but most of us are starving to death." So I invite you to come to my home and take a big bite out of life. The time is now.

name: Music City Hotel, Single Bed in 6-Bed Male Dorm Rm
description:
One single bed in a 6 bed male shared dormitory room.

Shared restrooms and showers located down the hall. Mini-fridge, sink, and medium size locker contained inside room. Linens, towels and bath amenities provided, as well as daily tidy up service and disinfecting of surfaces.
neighborhood_overview:
Music City Hotel is located in the vibrant Polk Gulch/Lower Nob Hill neighborhood. Immediately to the left when exiting the Hotel is Polk Street, filled with a wide array of incredible food options, shops, as well as unique bars and nightlife. The neighborhood has historical significance as the original center for San Francisco’s LGBT community and more recently has harbored members of the arts community and important music venues such as Kimo’s, Great American Music Hall, The Regency Ballroom, The Masonic Theater, and more.

In the 1960s at the height of the counterculture movement, a music venue in the neighborhood called The Avalon Ballroom played a vital role in hosting influential acts such as Moby Grape, Quicksilver Messenger Service, and the Grateful Dead. Fast forward to today, and the Polk Gulch has maintained its local charm of both new, modern and long-standing businesses that serve both the neighborhood and beyond.

Tourist attractions and neighborhoods
host_about: You will be energized by the past, present and future of music during your stay at Music City Hotel – a tribute to the robust musical history of the Bay Area, and dedicated towards nurturing its present and future. Immerse yourself in our stylishly decorated rooms while staying connected at the crossroads of the city’s present day music scene, along with its storied past.

neighborhood_overview:
🌵 The high desert refers to an area located on the western edge of the Mojave Desert, 2661 feet above sea level, also known as Antelope Valley or "the AV".

Locations used in movies, commercials and music videos 🎶 are scattered all over the valley. El Mirage Dry Lakebed wins the award for most used film location of all time.

Just up the road is Saddleback Butte State Park with the highest point in the Antelope Valley at 3,651 feet. Public campgrounds are situated at the base of the Mountain.

💀 The lowest elevation in North America at 282 feet below sea level is in Death Valley. A couple hours drive.

🐦 Rich in bird life. Many migratory species, and a few permanent residents: golden eagles, hawks, ravens, and owls, and some smaller birds such as rock and cactus wrens, thrashers, blackbirds, horned larks, ladderbacked woodpeckers, sparrows, finches, and loggerhead shrikes. name: Pet Friendly West Bedroom High Desert Home
description:
☕ One of three comfortable bedrooms available at this location.

Nearby biking, hiking, museums and movie locations for your enjoyment - one block from stores, restaurants and the public library.

🐶 Fenced-in yard is great for pets - contact host for rules and fees.

⛔ No kitchen or backyard use.

⚠There is no lake here - this house is quite unremarkable.
neighborhood_overview:
🌵 The high desert refers to an area located on the western edge of the Mojave Desert, 2661 feet above sea level, also known as Antelope Valley or "the AV".

Locations used in movies, commercials and music videos 🎶 are scattered all over the valley. El Mirage Dry Lakebed wins the award for most used film location of all time.

Just up the road is Saddleback Butte State Park with the highest point in the Antelope Valley at 3,651 feet. Public campgrounds are situated at the base of the Mountain.

💀 The lowest elevation in North America at 282 feet below sea level is in Death Valley. A couple hours drive.

🐦 Rich in bird life. Many migratory species, and a few permanent residents: golden eagles, hawks, ravens, and owls, and some smaller birds such as rock and cactus wrens, thrashers, blackbirds, horned larks, ladderbacked woodpeckers, sparrows, finches, and loggerhead shrikes. (don't worry, i haven't actually seen all these birds. just read about it

name: Oasis in the Desert on Tranquility Ct. Room 1
description: Beautifully decorated room in the 2nd story of Craftsman style modern KB home.  House was built in 2013.  Room is next to the loft with a 130' inch projection screen that guest can use if you would like to watch football/TV show on the big screen.  The house also has a glass-tiled Roman-style swimming pool with a Jacuzzi that guest can also enjoy during their stay.  Room has TV & cable.  Fresh pot of coffee in the kitchen for guests (or upon request).  Mini fridge & microwave in room to use.
neighborhood_overview: We live in a neighborhood that was established in 2013.  We are surrounded by desert on 3 sides so the area is very peaceful, there are less than 50 homes in the neighborhood.  Close to Lockheed, Northrop, close to shopping and restaurants.  About 10 minutes away from the 14 freeway.  This house is wonderful because we only have three houses block, we have a great view of the mountains and of the airplanes.  Sunsets in the Antelope Valley desert are amazing!  We are located down the street from the Lancaster National Soccer Park which is literally around the corner less than five minutes away.
host_about:
My husband James and I are both working professionals who commute to the San Fernando Valley for work.  We have no children but we do have 3 beautiful dogs, a husky/chow/lab mixed dog named Sammie, a corgi named Sawyer Quinn and our white husky Kassie.  We are all very down to earth people and will do anything to make a guest comfortable during their stay. 

My husband and I love to travel and we always take time to go on at least 1 vacation every year.  We have been to all 4 Hawaiian islands (Oahu, Maui, Big Island and Kauai)., New York City, Orlando, San Francisco, Puerto Rico etc.   

Our favorite place to visit is New York City.  We always try to catch a baseball game at Yankees Stadium whenever we come visit. 

The one thing that we always look for whenever we travel are having accommodations that are inviting and clean.  We believe that traveling to different places around the world make lasting memories.

description:
Newly remodeled 12'x12' boutique style bedroom, ensuite bathroom w/shower in a mid-century modern rancher. Full sized (54") bed. Sliding glass doors overlook a semi-private hillside garden. Unheated pool overlooks the San Gabriel Valley.
One yard area can be closed off for a dog to run.
Multiple HDMI input Smart TV, w/dedicated desktop computer, wireless mouse & keyboard. No need to bring a laptop, guests may log in to all their accounts. Ample parking. Separate Entertainment Room for dining.
neighborhood_overview:
The property is freeway close, but secluded due to its driveway (which also acts to discourage thieves). A single entry point for the entire neighborhood tract enhances safety from random crimes. Some family members like to walk down to the shopping center for exercise. Target, Walmart, 30+ restaurants are only a mile away.
Our hillside and private hilltop area are natural. It has squirrels, skunks, coyotes, reptiles, insects, spiders and birds. Hummingbirds often visit our feeders. Peacocks call from their home on a nearby hill. Bugs crawl into the house on occasion. Ants haven't been a problem since the yard was treated five years ago, but they could reappear any time. (SoCal has big problems with Argentinian ants.)
Dogs over 40 lbs are safe from coyotes which are always on the prowl. Small dogs must be watched or kept indoors; many neighbors have lost their pets. If you travel with your cat, you MUST keep it indoors. Coyotes don't approach humans, but you could see one a
host_about:
I am a married non-smoker, and mother of two adult sons. I grew up in California, have a BA in Biology from Revelle (UCSD). I spent 2+ years studying pharmacology in graduate school at UCI, and 2+ years studying electronics at DeVry, but have never worked in either field. The last paid work I did was tutoring calculus. 
My politics are liberal and I don't believe cannabis, alcohol and drugs are inherently evil. I do believe in evidence-based (scientific) thinking, women's rights, saving habitats for non-human species (thereby our own as well), and recycling. So, not a typical Alabaman. I live here because my better half has a job here that he really likes. His name is Jim, and I am literally (yes, I know what literal means) grateful on a daily basis that I had the good sense to marry him. We usually read two or three books a week. For Friday night excitement, we go to Barnes & Noble where I peruse the paranormal romances, fantasy and sci-fi sections while he looks at sci-fi and nonfiction. My favorite is the Anita Blake, Vampire Hunter series by Laurell Hamilton. My dream job would be an editor for a publisher's paranormal romance division, because that genre desperately needs editing, and I am a spelling and grammar nazi. Don't ever give me a sample of your writing to proof unless you have a strong ego. 
I have a fondness for Siamese cats (one in particular), but enjoy all mammals. In 2014, a nerve in my heart died, so now I have a pacemaker. I didn't have a heart attack, but a tibial injury in 2008 keeps me from biking or taking extended walks. For exercise, I restrain myself from criticizing other people's bad grammar and misspellings. 
I like to travel, camp in national parks, try new restaurants and review them on Yelp!, repair broken things, and solve sudoku and kenken puzzles. When I travel, I like to leave no trace of my having been there... other than the occasional repaired lamp. I don't use any social media. Instead I call, e-mail, and text. My current challenges are to rid our house of excessive books and finish home remodeling.

neighborhood_overview:
Sun Valley / Lake Los Angeles Buttes:
The region was once called Los Angeles Buttes, since they were the only ones in the northern part of the county. The eponymous lakes (one dedicated to fishing and one dedicated to swimming and boating) have dried up. The fishing lake was stocked with trout, bass and catfish. In 1967, during the 1960s land speculation boom in the Antelope Valley, land developers bought 4,000 acres (16 km2) in the region, subdivided it into 4,465 lots, and artificially refilled the natural lake and named it Lake Los Angeles as an enticement to land buyers. Advertisements showed a water skier on the lake (which was probably no more than 5 feet deep) and a showcase home on the top of the nearby hill, giving the impression of a resort town. There was a country club and a high-end restaurant that overlooked the large recreational lake. There was also a small store/bar and grill. description: We are locals who love hosting, and making friends, but also earn a living doing what we love.  We try to keep our rate as affordable as possible. We are not luxury homes/hotels with concierge, pools, gyms, etc. We offer safe and clean space. No frills, no hidden charges. Please be kind and respectful to us, other guests, and the neighbors. Please read and abide by our house rules. Please reach out if you have questions. Thank you for reading and looking forward to hosting you.
neighborhood_overview:
1025 W. 25th St. is located in the University Park neighborhood of Los Angeles. This area is known for its proximity to the University of Southern California (USC), which brings a lively, student-centric atmosphere to the neighborhood.

University Park features a mix of historic homes, modern apartment buildings, and a variety of dining and shopping options. The area has a vibrant community with cultural and educational institutions nearby, contributing to a dynamic urban environment.

You'll find tree-lined streets and parks, which offers recreational facilities and green space. The neighborhood's diversity is reflected in its range of architectural styles and local businesses. The presence of USC also means that there are often events, activities, and a youthful energy in the area.

Overall, University Park combines residential comfort with the hustle and bustle of city life, making it a unique and engaging place to live or visit.
host_about: Hi, I am Ron. I am in my 30s and I have lived in LA for the past 10 years. When I was in the military, I travelled to many places. I love making new friendship and connections. I hope to host you and answer any questions you might have about my listing or LA in general. Thank you for reading.

name: Sanctuary for the Traveler - Private Space
description:
Within walking distance of Mills College, Sanctuary is a private, clean and comfortable room in our artsy home, with free parking. We offer an affordable haven on a safe, tree-lined street in a multi-cultural middle-class neighborhood, and within proximity of major transport lines. Our family home is full of ...well...family life, with a 19-year old, and one parent who works from home, and the other off-site.

If you are comfortable with a diverse, multi-cultural community this is your place!
neighborhood_overview:
We love our street. Sweet neighbors who talk to each other. If you love connecting to diverse communities we are within walking distance of Mills College, and just down the road from Lakeshore Ave, area and the lively, downtown - uptown arts and food scene.
Add to that very easy, accessible public transportation to San Francisco and beyond, make this a fantastic place to launch your weekend or work-week.
host_about: I live in Oakland and my days are filled with my kids, my home, community and job.  Our 19 year-old daughter lives at home, and my 26 year-old son lives close by and comes to visit pretty often.  So with all that the house is a busy (sometimes messy version of life) but all good. We aren't a pristine B&B -- just a homey home with kids, dogs and kitty cats.  I was once a chef and owned a catering business but now I work helping elders move into assisted living care. Amy my partner is a theater professional - former Artistic Director of the Playwrights Foundation in San Francisco.  So if you like theater, futbol, food and wine you have come to the right place. And Maggie the dog and Rosie & Mocha the cats welcome you too.

It's 0.6 miles from the nearest strip of restaurants (called "Temescal"), and about 1 mile from the nearest BART station.

I'ts 0.7 miles from The Temescal Produce Market at 5121 Telegraph Ave, Oakland.

It's 1.1 miles from Whole Foods Market at 3000 Telegraph Ave in Berkeley

This is 1 bed in a Six-bed Mixed dorm.

California Dreams Hostel Ocean Beach, is located in the Ocean Beach neighborhood of San Diego, only a 10 minute bike ride from the beach.

It’s a place where backpackers from all over the world can meet like-minded travelers and have a true hostel experience with its fun community atmosphere and affordable prices, while enjoying excellent customer service, amenities, cleanliness, and comfort of staying at a quality hotel.
neighborhood_overview:
Ocean Beach often referred to as OB, is one of San Diego's best beach communities. This funky seaside town sits between the Pacific Ocean to the west and the more upscale enclave of Point Loma on the hill to the east. It is laid-back and less rowdy than the San Diego neighborhoods of Mission Beach and Pacific Beach a few miles north.

Although Ocean Beach sits on prime waterfront real estate, the neighborhood still exudes a small-town atmosphere, making it an ideal place to live and visit.
host_about: California Dreams Hostel – fun, friendly hostel that caters to independent travelers looking to explore Southern California and experience the beautiful city of San Diego on the shores of the Pacific Ocean. Our staff works hard to make our hostel a warm and welcoming place for our guest, providing the best experience possible, so you can find home away from home and make some unforgettable experiences. Staying with us is an opportunity to meet like-minded travelers from all over the world, make new friends, and experience San Diego like a local – the nightlife, the beaches, the history and the food!

We host long-term (At least 1 month) reservations for fully vaccinated engineers, interns, students, entrepreneurs, and travelers from around the world. Focused on technology, engineering, and startups, our tech island is a gateway to experience Silicon Valley and San Francisco.

We provide unlimited food for $10/day, which will save you hundreds of dollars and hours of convenience. Please see our photos of the food selection!

Welcome - you are going to love it!
neighborhood_overview:
We are very fortunate to live on the border of Campbell and San Jose, a very quiet and safe neighborhood. There is ample street parking.

Within 2 miles of the house:

Food: Chipotle, Pinkberry, Starbucks, Rubio's, Panera Bread, Subway, McDonalds, Burger King, Panda Express, The Melt, Taco Bell, Smash Burger, Buffalo Wild Wings, Chevy's, Sushi, Indian, Thai, Pizza, Hash House (breakfast)

Grocery: Safeway, Campbell farmers market, Whole Foods, Sprouts, Target, and Walmart

Things to do: Movie Theater, Santa Row, Bikram Yoga, Gold's Gym, Public Library, Running Trails, and Valley Fair Mall.

Door to door travel time:
Apple Campus - 10 mins
Santa Clara University - 11 mins
Downtown San Jose - 13 mins
San Jose Airport - 15 mins
Downtown Mt. View - 17 mins
(Hidden by Airbnb) Campus - 19 mins
Stanford University/Downtown Palo Alto - 21 mins
Henry Cowell Redwoods - 34 mins
Santa Cruz - 35 mins
host_about: I am an information junkie and I love learning about culture, food, and norms from other countries. I host with passion, and I welcome entrepreneurs, engineers, students, travelers, and tech enthusiasts. My goal is to make your stay easy, comfortable, and fun. Our community enjoys cooking, playing board games, hiking, running, yoga, playing sports, comparing international cultures, and debating/discussing tech, business strategy, world affairs, philosophy, etc. The food here is excellent. We provide a huge selection and variety of food, and we love to cook and share meals together.

name: HackerHome - Mountain View Caltrain
description:
The HackerHome Network

New to the Valley? Transitioning to the area? HackerHome can help.

We often organize family dinners, pitch events, and nature outings. You'll also have a chance to connect with current guests and grow your network in Silicon Valley.
neighborhood_overview:
Located in the heart of Mountain View just two blocks away from downtown! The location is ideal in terms of walkability.

0.4 mile to 500 Startups
1.1 miles to Y Combinator
1.6 miles to the Computer History Museum
2.3 miles to the big search engine company
2.3 miles to Hacker Dojo

For the neighborhood guidebook, please go to this listing: https://www.airbnb.com/rooms/2670018
then click on the maps tab.

name: Sequoia Redwood Garden in Sunnyvale
description: Come stay in comfort in a newly renovated condo surrounded by Redwoods in the heart of Silicon Valley. Easy access to highways 101, 237, & 85; short commutes to the tech companies or fun venues (SF, Monterey etc.) Please check the Airbnb rules: use a clear photo, correct names, & you cannot reserve for another person except as a business. Guests need to speak English. Follow COVID-19 guidelines. My daughter & her husband have completed their Covid-19 vaccinations; my final one is on 17 Mar 21.
neighborhood_overview:
We are in a quiet neighborhood in Sunnyvale - but you can do a lot of exploring for food, entertainment & outdoor activities here or nearby. Many “authentic” eateries exist close by (Japanese, Mexican, Indian...) as well as Fusion, Tapas, Burgers and Pizza. Also available: coffee houses, breweries and wineries (even in Sunnyvale ...!)

About 15-20 min to: Shoreline Amphitheater (concerts) & Computer History Museum, tech companies, NASA, Great America Theme Park, Levis Stadium (4 miles), Tech Museum, Flint Center. About 1.5 hour drive or less to Santa Cruz surfing, ~2 hours to Monterey.
host_about:
I am a Scientist (Environmental Microbiology / Analytical Chemistry) with a creative bent, & I really enjoy being an Airbnb Host. 

At home, I removed carpets, replacing that with hardwood flooring everywhere & wood stairs & tiling the Fireplace.
I also practiced & taught Aikido & I like to sing. My most exciting adventure was singing Beethovan's Ninth as part of the Penn State Choir in Carnegie Hall with the Pittsburgh Symphony Orchestra.

name: Furnished in Foothills 1
description: This property is very comfortable. It is a large house with 3 furnished rental bedrooms. We are near San Jose’s east foothills at the entrance to rustic Alum Rock Park. The 3 bedrooms are right next to each other.  You share a large TV room upstairs with DirecTV (I never use that room). neighborhood_overview: The Rock Canyon Circle makes a full circle off of Penitencia Creek Road. There are about 50 homes on the street that were built in the 1970’s and 1980’s. There is a creek flowing out of Alum Rock Park in the winter. The park is less than a quarter mile away. It attracts many hikers, runners, and bicyclists. There are several deer in the park, along with coyote, bobcats, foxes, owls, hawks, vultures, and wild turkey. Once in a while a mountain lion is spotted. The local neighborhood is quiet and friendly. There are usually Fourth of July block parties every year. There is an adult happy hour rotating around the neighborhood on a monthly basis.

neighborhood_overview: The Upper Monroe neighborhood has all the ingredients essential to comfortable city living - retail, restaurants and recreation - within walking distance of the house. Its boundaries are marked at the north by Route 490, south at the city line with the Town of Brighton, east on Culver Road, and west to Field Street.  The Monroe Avenue Strip, inside the Monroe Upper Village, includes a pet store, shoe repair, family market, hair salon, a gaming store and much more. Many Upper Monroe neighbors enjoy the weekly walk to the Monroe Village Farmers' Market, held each Wednesday at the Blessed Sacrament Church parking lot at Monroe Avenue and Oxford Street. Cobbs Hill Reservoir is a quick walk, as well as hiking on beautiful Pinnacle Hill just a few blocks from your front door. Bordering neighborhoods, such as Highland, Swillburg and Park Ave, are also some of the nicest in Rochester.

name: Cozy Private One Bedroom, Brooklyn
description: Important! If you definitely want the room for a certain time, Please make a reservation for the time you want it! If you're just looking around tho feel free to ask me anything!
host_about:
Hello! 

I have lived in New York City all my life, and have lived at my current place for two years.. I am a student in Environmental Science and play music in two bands around Brooklyn, one for children (for example birthday parties for 5 year olds) and one rock and roll band, but I don't drink or smoke (don't mind other people who do)... I read alot of books and listen to alot of radio shows about science and international news- I ride my bike everywhere. If you stay at my house I will try and find you a bike!

I've travelled a little bit, to Europe (Sweden, Slovenia, Spain, France, Holland, Belgium, Germany), and to Mexico (D.F. mostly) and Israel but haven't left ny in the past few years. 
In the summer I try to go to the beach as much as possible. In the winter I visit friend's houses and drink tea. One day I would like to visit Africa, South America, the Artic and Papua New Guinea, (if I can ever save the money for the airline ticket :)  )
I can't live without books, friends, going for a walk once a day, trying to learn other languages (speak spanish, working on french, have taken classes in Greek, Japanese, Hebrew and Portuguese), and my family (they live in San Francisco)..

Our house is medium sized, but it has plenty of space for privacy, if you need your space after a long trip-  or for hanging out- we have a projector sometimes watch movies or listen to records in the living room- As far as hosting goes, I love New York and have many friends involved in all sides of it, from the arts/ music scenes to restaurants to activism- I know most neighborhoods in the city pretty well and am always happy to give people advice on where to go and what to do so they don't just see the stuff everyone sees. 

嗨喽，我叫Jacques，（我不会讲中文，这个介绍是我的一个房客帮我翻译的）

我住在布鲁克林（Brooklyn）一个安全的街区。我有两个房间，一大一小。我的公寓附近有一些酒吧和餐厅，离威廉斯堡（Williamsburg）和劳德代尔堡（Fort Green）比较近。去曼哈顿下城区（Lower Manhattan）的话半小时就到了。

我是个玩音乐的土生土长的纽约客。我有个25岁的开服饰店的室友Cat。我们支持多元性取向人权并为LGBT友好。房子里很安静，偶尔有时候我朋友们会过来一起看电影听音乐。

公寓里有无线网，厨房，浴室，浴巾，房间里有个大床和换洗的床单被套。超市和洗衣店都与公寓只隔着一条街。你会有你自己的钥匙。房间适合两人住但是有一次招待房客四个人也挤下来了。

规则

唯一一条规则就是禁止抽烟，嗑药，宠物和来过夜的房客外的人。务必不要把吃的放在厨房的桌子上。出门的时候一定要用钥匙锁门（门不能自动锁）。退房的时候在门外把钥匙从大门中间的小凿丢进门里面就好了。

name: The Hideaway
description: The 'Hideaway' is a basic, no-frills guest room located in one of the best parts of West Harlem; nothing fancy.The apartment has a semi-private entrance in a basement unit. You've got your twin bed, desk, and closet. WiFi is included.
neighborhood_overview: I've lived in Harlem all my life. I've seen it in its many iterations from when it was considered unsafe to many outsiders to its emergence as a destination to live, dine, and hangout. It's wonderful time for those of us who have "stuck it out" through thick & thin. To me it has always been home and I'm grateful to still live here. It's a diverse place with something for everyone whether you are business driven, artistically minded, or musically inclined.
host_about: I was born and raised in Harlem. Harlem has always been about change and innovation. About every 30 years since the Dutch settled on  this section of New York called 'Nieuw Haarlem', there has been a drastic shift. For about 10 years Harlem been going through a second renaissance. The infusion of life that has come from Columbia University's campus expansion, seismic decrease in violent crime, and the explosion of the restaurant and nightlife scene has made this neighborhood THE coveted place following the trends of Hell's Kitchen and Williamsburg. I am grateful I can live in the midst of all these beautiful changes. It's my hope that visitors leave Harlem with a very positive impression of my neighborhood.

name: Perfectly Located UpperWest Futon
description:
Welcome to your perfect NYC getaway! I’m so excited to host you and share this space. I’ve proudly hosted since 2013, welcoming travelers from around the world.
Our apartment is just one block from Central Park and steps from the B and C subway lines—perfect for exploring NYC.
Enjoy amazing dining, shops, and bars within a block. Iconic spots like Lincoln Center, Hell's Kitchen, and Times Square are 15 minutes away.
Check out my guidebook for top recommendations to make your stay unforgettable!
neighborhood_overview: The Upper West Side is AMAZING! so many restaurants, bars and nightlife around here! We are very close to the super famous SMOKE jazz bar and 4 train stops away of the amazing RedRooster restaurant, just to mention a few. Central Park is literally around the corner and the Natural History Museum is easily accessible through the B/C 103rd st station which is also literally around the corner. Although all of this excitement is happening around us, our street is extremely quiet and friendly, it doesn't even feel like you are in crazy New York. I have a list of some of my favorite places to eat which I am more than happy to share with the guests! Let me know your budget and I will share some great spots!
host_about: I’m living the dream in New York City as a Life and Business Coach. With over 2.5 decades in the fashion industry, I’ve transitioned into a serial entrepreneur, artist, and sound healer. My work empowers others to step into their full potential. I’m passionate about helping people grow, and I love hosting guests from all walks of life. I can’t wait for you to experience NYC like a true New Yorker!

The house is located in a quiet neighborhood, within walking distance to Jacobi Medical Center, Calvary Hospital, the Jack D. Weiler Hospital of the Albert Einstein College of Medicine and the Montefiore Medical Center (Hutchinson Campus).

neighborhood_overview:
The Bronx has lots of neighborhoods, one of them is Pelham Parkway, not too far, not too close to downtown Manhattan. The house is located at the boundary with Morris Park Neighborhood. Walk to Luciano's and Emilio's Pizzerias, La Masa, and Patricia's Restaurants, Big Deals supermarket, or walk to White Plains Road/Lydig Ave shopping area and find pizzerias, supermarkets, fruits and vegetables stores, pharmacies, banks, starbucks, dunkin donuts, covenience stores, and more. About two blocks away, you will find The Pine, an Italian restaurant.
All previous guests find this neighborhood safe, nice, and quiet, only with the normal city noises. The house has a good size front yard and back yard with plenty of plants, the Bronx Zoo and the Botanical Garden are at walking distance, and three blocks away, guests can enjoy a walk on Moshoulu/Pelham Greenway to go to Pelham Bay Park, which is more than three times the size of Manhattan's Central Park. name: Study zone near Columbia ••
description:
Full-service (chore-free) private room by the Park, Columbus Sq. shopping, Broadway restaurants, Amsterdam nightlife, and the B/C and 1/2/3 trains, in renovated 4-bed 2-bath corner apt of elevator building 10-12 minutes walk from campus.

The experience here is tailored to fellow students, with shared amenities unavailable in campus housing, like fast WiFi, creative spaces, and furnishing. Regardless, all are welcome here.

NY taxes:
- Fewer than 180 days = 4.5%
- Fewer than 90 days = 10.5%
neighborhood_overview:
All the typical conveniences are nearby, including delis, bodegas, pharmacies, grocery stores, fitness studios, live performance venues, bars, and a variety of restaurants. The Columbus Square shopping center is a few minutes' walk South on Columbus, where there's a Whole Foods, cafes and shopping.

The neighborhood is diverse and is home to a lot of families and people of all ages. On many days, and especially on weekends, you can meet neighbors congregating on the streets and sidewalk to play dominos or have a cookout and listen to music. They're all very nice and have often invited guests to join their gatherings.

These gatherings are rarely very noisy. At most you may hear distant shuffling dominos, Bachata and R&B music, or laughing conversation. It’s generally much quieter than the touristy areas south of here or the party scene to the north. It’s the perfect escape if you need a break from the bustle of Midtown or are looking for a relaxing place to study.
host_about:
Stacy [she/they] is a projects coordinator and educator with CIDNY and her partner Tyler [he/they] is a computer science student researcher and developer at the school. 

Stacy manages the apartment and is who you will probably see most often. Tyler takes care of facilities and is available to help if anything needs fixing, cleaning, or improvement. All are welcome in our home and we guarantee a 5-star stay to every guest.

The Columbus Square shopping center is a few minutes' walk South on Columbus, where there's a Whole Foods, cafes and shopping.

The neighborhood is diverse and is home to a lot of families and people of all ages. On many days, and especially on weekends, you can meet neighbors congregating on the streets and sidewalk to play dominos or have a cookout and listen to music. They're all very nice and have often invited guests to join their gatherings.

These gatherings are rarely very noisy. At most you may hear distant shuffling dominos, Bachata and R&B music, or laughing conversation. It’s generally much quieter than the touristy areas south of here or the party scene to the north. It’s the perfect escape if you need a break from the bustle of Midtown or are looking for a relaxing place to study.
